  "chapter": {
    "number": 1,
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "content": [
          "Everything Is Futile"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 1,
        "content": [
          "These are the words of the Teacher,",
          {
            "noteId": 1538
          },
          "the son of David, king in Jerusalem:"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 2,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "“Futility",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "noteId": 1539
          },
          {
            "text": "of futilities,”",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "says the Teacher,",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "“futility of futilities!",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "Everything is futile!”",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 3,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What does a man gain from all his labor,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "at which he toils under the sun?",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 4,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Generations come and generations go,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "but the earth remains forever.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 5,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The sun rises and the sun sets;",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "it hurries back to where it rises.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 6,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The wind blows southward,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "then turns northward;",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "round and round it swirls,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "ever returning on its course.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 7,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "All the rivers flow into the sea,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "yet the sea is never full;",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "to the place from which the streams come,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "there again they flow.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 8,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "All things are wearisome,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "more than one can describe;",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "the eye is not satisfied with seeing,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "nor the ear content with hearing.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 9,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What has been will be again,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and what has been done will be done again;",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "there is nothing new under the sun.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 10,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Is there a case where one can say,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "“Look, this is new”?",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "It has already existed",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "in the ages before us.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 11,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "There is no remembrance",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "of those who came before,",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "and those yet to come will not be remembered",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "by those who follow after.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "content": [
          "With Wisdom Comes Sorrow"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 12,
        "content": [
          "I, the Teacher, was king over Israel in Jerusalem."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 13,
        "content": [
          "And I set my mind to seek and explore by wisdom all that is done under heaven. What a heavy burden God has laid upon the sons of men to occupy them!"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 14,
        "content": [
          "I have seen all the things that are done under the sun, and have found them all to be futile, a pursuit of the wind."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 15,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What is crooked cannot be straightened,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and what is lacking cannot be counted.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 16,
        "content": [
          "I said to myself, “Behold, I have grown and increased in wisdom beyond all those before me who were over Jerusalem, and my mind has observed a wealth of wisdom and knowledge.”"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 17,
        "content": [
          "So I set my mind to know wisdom and madness and folly; I learned that this, too, is a pursuit of the wind."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 18,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "For with much wisdom comes much sorrow,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and as knowledge grows, grief increases.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "footnotes": [
      {
        "noteId": 1538,
        "caller": "+",
        "text": "Or the Convener or the Preacher or the leader of the assembly; Hebrew Qoheleth is rendered as the Teacher throughout Ecclesiastes.",
        "reference": {
